19":"1319","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Layer Marney, Essex, England":"Layer Marney, Essex, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Yaxley, Suffolk, England":"Yaxley, Suffolk, England","of Layer Marney, Essex Co, England":"Layer Marney, Essex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Layer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Franz, Hans.","English: habitational name from any of the three places in Essex – Layer Breton, Layer de la Haye, and Layer Marney – all named from a river name, <i>Leire</i>, the name of a small stream, thought to be from a Celtic word meaning ‘mud’.","English: nickname or status name from Anglo-Norman French <i>le eyr</i> ‘the heir’. Compare   Ayer  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ayer","meanings":["English and Scottish: from Middle English <i>eir</i>, <i>eyr</i> ‘heir’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>heyr</i>, Old French <i>(h)eir</i>, Latin <i>heres</i>). Forms such as <i>Richard le Heyer</i> were frequent in Middle English, denoting a man who was well known to be the heir to the main property in a particular locality, either one who had already inherited or one with great expectations.","English: from the Anglo-Norman French and Middle English personal name <i>Aier</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Agihari</i>).","English: variant of   Hair  ."]},{"name":"Layher","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt.","German: variant of   Layer   4."]},{"name":"Lear","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>ler</i> ‘cheek, face, countenance, complexion’ (Old English <i>hlēor</i>), used adjectivally to mean ‘beautiful of face’.","English: variant of   Layer  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Uidhir</b> ‘son of the swarthy lad’ or ‘son of the servant of <i>Odhar</i>’, a byname from <i>odhar</i> (genitive <i>uidhir</i>) ‘dun-colored’, ‘weatherbeaten’. Compare   McAleer  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Layer was born in 1350, in Layer Marney, Essex, England, United Kingdom, her father, Richard le Lacer Mayor of London, was 51 and her mother, Juliana Asshewy, was 47. She married Sir Robert De Marney about 1369, in Layer Marney, Essex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1398, at the age of 48."},"et":{"1350–1398":"1350–1398","1317–1386":"1317–1386","1322–1360":"1322–1360","1324–Female":"1324–Surnud","1326–1365":"1326–1365","1328–Female":"1328–Surnud","1319–1400":"1319–1400","1370–1414":"1370–1414","1300–1376":"1300–1376","1304–1360":"1304–1360","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","before 1317":"enne 1317","1304":"1304","1414":"1414","1326":"1326","1324":"1324","1400":"1400","Abt 1376":"umbes 1376","1300":"1300","1322":"1322","about 1369":"umbes 1369","1398":"1398","1376":"1376","1365":"1365","1386":"1386","1319":"1319","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Layer Marney, Essex, England":"Layer Marney, Essex, England","Essex, England":"Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Buckinghamshire,